I feel like we were recently in the Era of Meme Stocks, but now that ended =
and we are in an Era of Banking Crises, and it=E2=80=99s a bit silly to tal=
k about the meme stocks. But they still exist! They=E2=80=99re still doing =
stuff! We have talked a bunch about AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=
=99s   APE gambit. Basically:
=09AMC was a meme stock and issued tons of stock to shore up its balance sh=
eet, pay down debt, and go off on larks like   buying a gold mine.=09Eventu=
ally it ran out of authorized shares to sell.=09It asked its shareholders t=
o approve more shares, but that would require a majority of all of the shar=
es to vote in favor of an amendment to the corporate charter, and retail sh=
areholders stereotypically don=E2=80=99t vote. So AMC couldn=E2=80=99t get =
enough votes, so it withdrew the request.=09Also some of its shareholders o=
bjected to the dilution that would come from issuing new shares, though it=
=E2=80=99s hard to know how much that objection mattered versus just the fa=
ct that most of its shareholders don=E2=80=99t vote at all. Not voting is e=
quivalent to voting no, and it seems like AMC=E2=80=99s biggest problem was=
 shareholder apathy rather than shareholder opposition.=09AMC came up with =
a=C2=A0very=C2=A0silly workaround. It issued a new weird class of stock cal=
led APEs, AMC Preferred Equity Units. Each APE has the same economic and vo=
ting rights as a=C2=A0common share, and AMC gave out one APE for each commo=
n share. Then it sold a bunch more APEs to raise cash.=09The APEs trade at =
a discount to the common stock, which makes this strategy sort of awful and=
 dilutive: You are selling something that is economically equivalent to the=
 common, but at a huge discount.=C2=A0=09So AMC asked its shareholders agai=
n to approve issuing more shares and=C2=A0converting=C2=A0the APEs into com=
mon, which will result in AMC being able to sell lots more regular common s=
tock.=09It also stacked this vote, because (1) the APEs=C2=A0vote alongside=
 the common, (2) there are now=C2=A0more=C2=A0APEs=C2=A0than common shares =
and=C2=A0(3) the APE holders have an incentive to vote to allow the convers=
ion, since the common trades at a much higher price than the APEs.=09Also t=
hough,=C2=A0(4) the APEs are  structured in a clever way to make sure that =
they=C2=A0all=C2=A0vote. Technically APEs are not shares but depositary rec=
eipts for 1/100th of a share of preferred stock. All the preferred stock is=
 held by a depositary, and the depositary has agreed to vote all of its pre=
ferred shares, in proportion to how the APE holders instruct it. So if 40% =
of the APEs vote yes, 10% vote no, and 50% never return a proxy, the actual=
 vote will be 80% yes and 20% no. Not voting an APE is=C2=A0not=C2=A0equiva=
lent to voting no.=09AMC scheduled the shareholder vote for yesterday.=09So=
me  shareholders sued, saying that this whole structure is ridiculous and d=
isenfranchises shareholders.

When we  talked about this last month, the shareholders and AMC had reached=
 an agreement to delay the lawsuit until April and hold the shareholder vot=
e on schedule, but not actually issue more shares or convert the APEs until=
 the lawsuit is resolved. AMC agreed to count votes separately, that is, to=
 report (1) how many common shares voted yes, how many voted=C2=A0no, and h=
ow many didn=E2=80=99t vote, (2) how many preferred shares voted yes becaus=
e the APE holders voted yes, how many preferred shares voted no because the=
 APE holders voted no, and how many preferred shares voted yes/no because A=
PE holders didn=E2=80=99t vote but the depositary voted the shares anyway.
The results of that vote will, I think, be interesting for the lawsuit. Bas=
ically if the common shareholders all vote no and the APEs all vote yes, th=
at supports the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claim that this was all a trick to dise=
nfranchise shareholders. But if the common shareholders=C2=A0mostly don=E2=
=80=99t vote, but the ones who do vote vote yes, then that supports AMC=E2=
=80=99s view that this was all a trick to=C2=A0help=C2=A0shareholders who w=
ould otherwise just fail to vote for something that they actually want. I w=
rote:
If a majority of the common shares that vote vote yes, and the APEs also vo=
te yes, but the amendment fails to get a majority of all of the common shar=
es =E2=80=94 if 40% of the common votes yes, 20% votes no, and 40% doesn=E2=
=80=99t vote at all, say =E2=80=94 then in April AMC will have a decent arg=
ument to the judge to the effect of: =E2=80=9CLook, yes, we did this to get=
 around the strict letter of the voting requirements, but as you see, even =
with all the publicity this has generated, our shareholders never vote. So =
we are doing what we think is best for them and also what a majority of the=
m, as best we can tell, actually want.=E2=80=9D I am not sure that a judge =
would allow the amendment, in this case, but it would be a bit harsh to sto=
p it.
Well that=E2=80=99s what happened. AMC held its shareholder vote yesterday =
and:
=0925.5% of the common stock voted to authorize more shares, 9.1% voted no,=
 0.5% abstained (like, affirmatively chose to vote, but marked =E2=80=9Cabs=
tain=E2=80=9D) and the other 64.8% just didn=E2=80=99t vote.=0957.1% of the=
 APES voted yes, 5.2% no, 0.5% abstained and 37.3% didn=E2=80=99t vote.=09B=
ut because of the preferred-stock voting mechanic, that meant that 91% of t=
