gold mine</a>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually it ran o=
ut of authorized shares to sell.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I=
t asked its shareholders to approve more shares, but that would require a m=
ajority of all of the shares to vote in favor of an amendment to the corpor=
ate charter, and retail shareholders stereotypically don=E2=80=99t vote. So=
 AMC couldn=E2=80=99t get enough votes, so it withdrew the request.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also some of its shareholders objected to=
 the dilution that would come from issuing new shares, though it=E2=80=99s =
hard to know how much that objection mattered versus just the fact that mos=
t of its shareholders don=E2=80=99t vote at all. Not voting is equivalent t=
o voting no, and it seems like AMC=E2=80=99s biggest problem was shareholde=
r apathy rather than shareholder opposition.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">AMC came up with a=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>silly workaround. It =
issued a new weird class of stock called APEs, AMC Preferred Equity Units. =
Each APE has the same economic and voting rights as a=C2=A0common share, an=
d AMC gave out one APE for each common share. Then it sold a bunch more APE=
