ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> talked about this last month</a>, the shareholders =
and AMC had reached an agreement to delay the lawsuit until April and hold =
the shareholder vote on schedule, but not actually issue more shares or con=
vert the APEs until the lawsuit is resolved. AMC agreed to count votes sepa=
rately, that is, to report (1) how many common shares voted yes, how many v=
oted=C2=A0no, and how many didn=E2=80=99t vote, (2) how many preferred shar=
es voted yes because the APE holders voted yes, how many preferred shares v=
oted no because the APE holders voted no, and how many preferred shares vot=
ed yes/no because APE holders didn=E2=80=99t vote but the depositary voted =
the shares anyway.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The results of that vote will, I think, be int=
eresting for the lawsuit. Basically if the common shareholders all vote no =
and the APEs all vote yes, that supports the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claim that=
 this was all a trick to disenfranchise shareholders. But if the common sha=
reholders=C2=A0<em>mostly don=E2=80=99t vote</em>, but the ones who do vote=
 vote yes, then that supports AMC=E2=80=99s view that this was all a trick =
to=C2=A0<em>help=C2=A0</em>shareholders who would otherwise just fail to vo=
te for something that they actually want. I wrote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a majority of the common shares=
 <em>that vote</em> vote yes, and the APEs also vote yes, but the amendment=
 fails to get a majority of <em>all</em> of the common shares =E2=80=94 if =
40% of the common votes yes, 20% votes no, and 40% doesn=E2=80=99t vote at =
all, say =E2=80=94 then in April AMC will have a decent argument to the jud=
ge to the effect of: =E2=80=9CLook, yes, we did this to get around the stri=
ct letter of the voting requirements, but as you see, even with all the pub=
licity this has generated, our shareholders never vote. So we are doing wha=
t we think is best for them and also what a majority of them, as best we ca=
n tell, actually want.=E2=80=9D I am not <em>sure</em> that a judge would a=
llow the amendment, in this case, but it would be a bit harsh to stop it.</=
p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well that=E2=80=99s what happened. AMC held it=
s shareholder vote yesterday <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30845777.258426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVz=
L2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDAxMTA0NjU5MjMwMzI0MDkvdG0yMzk0OTdkMV84ay5odG0=
